<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 94 / Technology (Worth Watching): Papaya's new role as a
contraceptive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DELLA BRADSHAW
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Eating a papaya fruit can be a powerful method of contraception in women.
Scientific researchers at the University of Sussex, in Brighton, have shown
that papain, an enzyme found in papaya, attacks progesterone, a critical
hormone for conception and pregnancy. When the papain interacts with a
particular protein in the blood it becomes up to 24 times as powerful as
when in its natural state.
The findings, which could lead to new methods of contraception, will not be
news to women in India and Sri Lanka, who have been eating papaya for
generations to prevent conception.
University of Sussex, UK, 0273 678453.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
