<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 94 / Major steers clear of pitfalls in Moscow: How Number 10's
new press secretary managed overseas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There was an air of quiet celebration in 10 Downing Street yesterday. Mr
John Major's three-day visit to Moscow may not have been the most exciting
of events. But nor had it been, like most previous trips, a disaster.
The Westminster journalists who have dogged and disrupted the prime minister
on earlier ventures abroad came home late on Wednesday night more or less
empty-handed.
There were occasional mishaps for Mr Major in Moscow. The tabloids mocked
his appearance in a Russian fur hat. The television cameras caught him
looking awkwardly unsure of himself during an official dinner with Mr Boris
Yeltsin, the Russian president.
But this was nothing compared with the string of disasters that accompanied
his Far East tour last autumn. The agenda then had been set entirely by the
press and Mr Major had been bombarded about the divisions and unrest in the
Conservative party. He was provoked into a series of intemperate attacks on
his critics and the resultant headlines were universally bad.
In Moscow it was different, although the government is still beset by
domestic trouble. Just before his departure another junior member of the
government was obliged to resign because of personal conduct. The
back-to-basics initiative has been reduced to a shambles.
But on this occasion Mr Major decided to set his own terms for contacts with
the travelling press - which dominate news coverage of such visits. He
decided from the outset that he would not be harried by the inevitable
questions about domestic difficulties.
In interviews and press conferences during the trip he politely rebuffed
questions on back to basics or the sexual proclivities of members of his
government.
There were no angry outbursts, no ill-judged answers. Instead Mr Major
insisted on talking about the issues behind his Moscow talks - the situation
in Bosnia, Anglo-Russian relations and the stalling pace of economic reform
in Russia.
Much of the credit for the careful news management was given to Mr
Christopher Meyer, the prime minister's newly appointed press secretary.
On his first foreign trip Mr Meyer was determined to maintain control of the
press. So he mixed blunt warnings that the prime minister would not respond
to questions about back to basics with a carefully timed flow of 'news
nuggets' to keep the media - and especially the tabloid newspapers -
occupied.
By and large it worked.
Mr Major's own attitude may have been the critical factor. After enduring
the worst press of any prime minister since Mr Harold Wilson in 1968, Mr
Major appeared ready to take the advice of his ministerial colleagues and
officials to inject distance and formality into his links with journalists.
Hence there were none of the off-the-cuff conversations which have
previously got him into so much trouble. His appearances were carefully
controlled and always tape-recorded by aides.
Having succeeded in Moscow, Mr Major, with the help of Mr Meyer, is
promising more of the same when he meets President Bill Clinton for a
potentially difficult meeting in Washington in 10 days.
The prime minister knows he cannot afford to provide the excuse that critics
are looking for to pronounce the death of the special relationship.
Some are already suggesting his relations with Mr Clinton are as brusque as
those between Mr Neil Kinnock, then Labour leader, and former president
Ronald Reagan during the 1980s.
On the evidence of Moscow, Mr Major should succeed. He certainly needs to.
The domestic pressures on his premiership over the next few months will be
bad enough even without any more accidents abroad.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9199 General Government, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
