<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 94 / MRes to act as PhD filter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Plans for a 'research masters' degree to be taken by all students aiming for
science doctorates were announced yesterday Mr William Waldegrave, the
science minister.
The qualification, which the government hopes will be offered from September
1995, is intended to cut the amount of research council funding for students
who fail to complete their doctorates. Of those who started science
doctorates using government research council grants in 1988, 40 per cent had
not completed their doctorates four years later.
Employers had also expressed concern that their recruits who had taken
doctorates had inadequate communication skills and were too 'narrowly
focused', with a poor grasp of management, according to officials.
Mr Waldegrave suggested that the new qualification, provisionally known as
the MRes, should take one year to achieve and include a significant research
component, accounting for 60 per cent of students' time.
It would include a grounding in research techniques and modules designed to
provide 'transferable skills' - including management, team working, and
communication - to enable scientists to explain their work to lay audiences.
New Structure for Postgraduate Research Training. Office of Science and
Technology, Albany House, 84-86 Petty France, London SW1H 9ST. Free.
</TEXT>
