<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 94 / Ministers back Tec-chamber mergers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A pilot scheme of voluntary mergers between chambers of commerce and
Training and Enterprise Councils won government approval yesterday. The
scheme's aim is to stimulate local business activities.
The announcement was made by Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry
secretary, and Mr David Hunt, employment secretary, in a letter to the
Association of British Chambers of Commerce and the Tec National Council.
The organisations welcomed the government's decision and pointed out that
some chambers and Tecs had already been working more closely. The proposed
bodies would offer benefits to local business by reducing duplication of
activities.
The British Chambers of Commerce says it represents more than 200,000
companies, which amounts to 40 per cent of all businesses. There are 82 Tecs
operating in England and Wales.
The BCC and the Tec National Council emphasised yesterday there would be no
pressure applied to secure mergers. No more than 10 mergers are likely this
year.
Both organisations insisted yesterday that where mergers took place it was
'absolutely critical' that the new bodies met local business needs, and that
merging would 'in due course enable them to equal or better their French or
German equivalents'.
Ministers are keen to ensure that any merged Tecs and chambers should be
created under an agreed framework of guidance which is approved by them.
They also want the new bodies to play a strategic role and exercise an
overview of all training and enterprise issues in their areas, including the
creation and popularising of business links. The government insists that the
merged bodies should represent the full range of local employers and not
just those who belong to them.
The proposed articles of association for such bodies have to make clear they
will not become involved in direct delivery of services except with the
explicit permission of government departments responsible for funding the
relevant service.
Separate organisations will have to be set up where one of the parties to a
merger already acts as a large-scale deliverer of training programmes. Mr
Heseltine and Mr Hunt said in their letter: 'We will need to ensure we have
legal advice on any contractual implications.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
