<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 94 / Councils 'fail to win hearts'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Market research by the Local Government Commission for England in the next
13 counties for which it must make proposals for council reorganisation has
found a confused picture.
It reveals a strong preference for devolved government to small local areas
 -beyond the scope of the current review - but little enthusiasm for either
the present districts or counties.
Overall, most people identify most strongly with their immediate local
community. Only about half feel strong local identity with their district
councils - about the same proportion who identify strongly with their
counties.
A majority of residents in virtually all the counties surveyed favoured the
general principle of unitary authorities - that all services should be
provided by one council rather than being split between counties and
districts - although nowhere was there an overwhelming majority.
MORI, the research company, has completed its polling for the commission in
Bedfordshire, Cheshire, Devon, Dorset, Essex, Hereford &amp; Worcester, Kent,
Norfolk, Northumberland, Suffolk, Surrey, Warwickshire, and Wiltshire.
Submissions from councils in these areas are due within the next month, with
proposals from the commission following by the end of August.
Humberside County Council is applying for judicial review of the
commission's proposal that it should be abolished. Avon, Cleveland,
Derbyshire and Somerset have already challenged similar plans to replace
them with unitary authorities.
</TEXT>
<XX>
