<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 94 / Labour police plans defeated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE and KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An opposition attempt to end the home secretary's responsibility for
policing in London was defeated in the Lords yesterday after the government
unexpectedly resurrected plans for an advisory committee.
Labour and Liberal Democrat peers argued during the committee stage of the
police and magistrates courts bill for the establishment of a police
authority in London similar to those which supervise the other 50 British
forces.
Earl Ferrers, Home Office minister of state, said the government would
proceed instead with proposals published in a white paper last year for a
committee of 12 Home Office appointees to advise the home secretary on
London policing.
A Labour amendment to establish an authority was defeated by 151 votes to
112. The government's main problems on the bill remain unresolved, however.
Backbench Tory peers have twice forced Mr Michael Howard, home secretary, to
retreat on plans to increase government control of police authorities.
Conservative peers have now tabled a number of further amendments on the
government's plans for performance targets for police forces and fixed-term
contracts for senior officers.
The government's proposals to reshape police authorities have been under
consistent attack since they were announced a year ago. Yet ministers
appeared genuinely unaware of the full strength or character of the
opposition until days before the bill started its parliamentary passage in
the Lords last month. Mr Howard has been on the defensive ever since.
His first concession, aimed at concern about proposals to appoint
independent members to police authorities, was to produce a procedure
distancing ministers from the initial selection process. In the face of
cross-party criticism in the Lords he then scrapped plans to let the home
secretary appoint heads of authorities, and agreed to greater flexibility in
authority size.
But ministers had again miscalculated. There were still enough Tory rebels
to maintain a risk of defeat when the bill returned to the Lords this week.
Opponents are now making further demands. They want local authority
councillors to retain a statutory majority on the new-style authorities,
with the independent members co-opted by the authorities themselves rather
than appointed by the home secretary.
The government insists its proposals would enhance local control but senior
police officers fear that, combined with provision in the bill for the home
secretary to set national policing objectives, they would increase
centralisation.
Mr Howard might decide to use the government's Commons majority to try to
implement his proposals. But this would not resolve what is in many ways the
biggest difficulty. This bill and the criminal justice bill are the
government's centrepieces of the parliamentary session, designed to
demonstrate that it is getting to grips with law and order.
To succeed, the programme needs the active co-operation of the police
service and police authorities - as ministers must have been aware when they
decided to abandon most of the more controversial recommendations of the
Sheehy report on police pay and conditions.
Imposing changes that have been vocally attacked by influential Conservative
peers and several former home secretaries might damage morale to a degree
that would outweigh the improved efficiency which, Mr Howard believes, would
flow from his reforms.
Mr Howard yesterday published proposals that will allow appeals against
unduly lenient sentences in serious and complex fraud cases. The
attorney-general will be given the power to refer such cases for
reconsideration by the Court of Appeal under amendments to the criminal
justice bill.
</TEXT>
