<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 94 / Mirror to raise bid for Independent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The consortium backed by Mirror Group Newspapers is preparing to increase
its bid for Newspaper Publishing, owners of The Independent and the
Independent on Sunday.
No final decision has been taken but discussions took place yesterday
involving Hambros and Schroders, representing members of the consortium, and
SG Warburg, which acts for Newspaper Publishing. Earlier this month the
consortium, which apart from MGN, includes the two largest existing
shareholders of The Independent, El Pais of Spain and La Repubblica of Italy
and a group of founders led by Mr Andreas Whittam Smith, bid 261.6p a share
for the company.
The bid was immediately trumped by Mr Tony O'Reilly's Independent Newspapers
of Ireland which bought 24.99 per cent of the company at 350p a share. The
consortium already controls just under 48 per cent of Newspaper Publishing.
An increased offer to persuade some of the remaining institutional
shareholders of the company to sell would give the consortium a majority
stake and allow it to go ahead with its plans.
These include following MGN staff to Canary Wharf in London's Docklands and
offering MGN a contract to provide all the services the paper needs apart
from editorial.
Talks could continue over the weekend with a planned meeting between Mr
O'Reilly and Mr Whittam Smith.
Meanwhile Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, said
yesterday in a written answer that he had received an application from the
consortium to acquire a controlling interest in Newspaper Publishing. The
consortium is asking that such a deal should not be referred to the
Monopolies Commission.
Mr Heseltine can allow the transfer of ownership of a newspaper without an
inquiry if he is satisfied 'the newspaper concerned is not economic as a
going concern and as a separate newspaper'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Mirror Group Newspapers.
    Newspaper Publishing.
    Independent Newspapers.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
