<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 94 / Consumer surveys at odds over recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More conflicting signals about the state of economic recovery emerged this
week with two surveys of consumer confidence, Graham Bowley writes.
A Barclaycard/Gallup survey published yesterday showed that two-thirds of
consumers remained unconvinced that Britain was coming out of the recession.
In contrast the Birmingham Midshires Building Society, in a survey conducted
by ICM Research, reported that consumer confidence was at its highest level
for four months.
Mr Mike McManus, Barclaycard commercial director, said: 'A large number of
consumers are still saying they are unconvinced that recovery is on the
way.'
But Mr Mike Jackson, Birmingham Midshires chief executive, said: 'Everything
is now right for sustained recovery across industry, manufacturing and in
the high street.'
Barclaycard found some reasons for optimism. The survey showed that pressure
on household budgets may be easing and consumers could return to certain
forms of credit.
