FT  18 FEB 94 / World Trade News: Hosokawa orders rapid measures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japan's prime minister, Mr Morihiro Hosokawa, told ministries yesterday to
draft emergency market-opening measures, possibly before the end of next
week, to contain the growing trade friction with the US, Reuter reports from
Tokyo.
A special cabinet meeting was also expected today to speed up drafting of
the 'voluntary' measures he promised after last week's US-Japan summit broke
down over Washington's demands for numerical market access targets.
Mr Masayoshi Takemura, chief cabinet secretary, said: 'We must draw up more
concrete and visible measures as soon as possible. . . Hosokawa and the top
(trade) negotiators agreed that the ball is in Japan's court.'
As for specific timing for the new measures, he said: 'As soon as possible,
maybe before the next G7 gathering.' Finance ministers and central bank
governors from the Group of Seven top industrialised nations meet in
Frankfurt, Germany on February 26.
Mr Takemura said the two nations should calm down and halt the trans-Pacific
war of words. 'In the last stage of the Japan-US framework talks, the two
sides agreed to a cooling-off period.'
