<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 94 / Blockade by Greece puts EU on spot
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Greece's blockade against Macedonia could cause a serious diplomatic split
within the European Union and further complicate European policy towards
Bosnia, Brussels officials warned yesterday.
With Greece giving little warning of its intentions to its European
partners, Commission officials yesterday indicated that they had been both
surprised and angered by Greece's action, not least because it currently
holds the EU presidency.
'It is bad enough for a member state to act like this, but it is even worse
when they are heading the union,' commented one senior Commission official,
who feared the action could inflame Balkan tensions.
Mr Hans Van Den Broek, commissioner for external affairs, yesterday flew to
Athens, where he was due to meet Greek officials. His visit forms part of a
regular meeting between Russia, and foreign ministers from the three members
of the EU troika: Germany, Greece and Belgium. However, EU officials
yesterday indicated that Mr Van Den Broek was likely to seek to use the
meeting to pressure Greece over the issue.
Mr Nicolaas Wegter, Commission spokesman, said yesterday: 'We are concerned
about the situation and therefore are asking for clarification (from the
Greeks).'
France, Germany and Belgium yesterday all expressed their concern over
Greece's refusal to let Macedonia use the port of Thessaloniki, Macedonia's
main outlet to the sea.
Meanwhile, Denmark yesterday asked for the European foreign ministers to
discuss the issue when they meet in Brussels on Monday.
With some officials now suggesting that Greece's action may contravene EU
regulations governing trade and foreign relations, the Commission's legal
services have been asked to consider the legality of Greece's action.
However, diplomats yesterday indicated that Greece's move, which comes after
a month in which it has sought to distance itself from Nato's threat of air
strikes against the Bosnian Serbs, has left many diplomats uncertain about
what action can be used against Greece.
In spite of the deep irritation felt by some Commission officials, fears
about creating a deep rift in the Union has left many unwilling to demand
any co-ordinated European action against Greece yet, not least because it is
still too early to be sure what the blockade of the port will precisely
entail.
'If it's a matter of oil, that is serious and that will be a big problem.
But reports suggest that it might be less than that,' commented one
diplomat.
</TEXT>
