<HEADLINE>
FT  18 FEB 94 / Bosnian Serbs begin pull-back from Sarajevo: Russians secure
agreement from Karadzic that ceasefire will be observed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bosnian Serbs began a large-scale withdrawal of their heavy weapons from
around Sarajevo yesterday, after dramatic intervention by Russia to avert
Nato air strikes against the Serbs.
Moscow secured a pull-back agreement with an assurance that it would send in
800 Russian troops to join the United Nations peacekeeping force in and
around the Bosnian capital. Most western countries, meanwhile, refused to
send additional troops to bolster the UN operation.
'We do think that war in Sarajevo is finally over,' Mr Radovan Karadzic, the
Bosnian Serb leader, said after meeting Russian envoy Mr Vitaly Churkin at
Pale, northeast of Sarajevo.
A UN official said a 'very significant' withdrawal of Bosnian Serb forces
was taking place. 'We are talking about convoys of equipment moving off the
hills.'
In Brussels, Nato said it stood by its ultimatum to the Bosnian Serbs to
withdraw heavy weapons more than 20km from the centre of Sarajevo or put
them under UN control under pain of air strikes. Pressure would not be
lifted until Nato was sure the Serbs had complied.
In Washington, the White House welcomed the Serb promise to Moscow but
expressed surprise that the Russians were sending UN peacekeepers to
Sarajevo.
Mr Douglas Hurd, UK foreign secretary, welcomed the Russian initiative,
adding: 'There is now a much better chance than before of avoiding air
strikes.'
Russia's decision to send more troops to Sarajevo arose directly from
discussions between Mr John Major, the prime minister, and President Yeltsin
in Moscow, Mr Jonathan Aitken, minister for defence procurement, told the
Commons last night.
Mr Churkin said 400 Russian troops under UN command in Croatia would be sent
immediately to the Sarajevo area and 400 more would be sent from Russia.
Mr Churkin went to Pale after two days of talks with President Slobodan
Milosevic of Serbia to try to defuse the Bosnian crisis.
The Russian leadership is anxious not to be sidelined as Nato and Washington
assume a stronger role in Bosnia. It also has to take account of nationalist
feeling at home sympathetic to the Serbs. In an interview on Russian
television, Mr Churkin said: 'We can say that any air strikes on any Bosnian
Serb positions are ruled out for the simple reason there will be no targets
for these strikes to hit.'
Mr Karadzic said: 'We are very grateful to Russia for its involvement in the
resolution of the crisis.' The Bosnian Serbs had accepted the Russian
'request' that they withdraw heavy weaponry from around Sarajevo and observe
a ceasefire.
Defence ministers from several Nato countries will meet in Italy on Sunday,
just hours before the expiry of the Nato deadline. If withdrawal and
collection of heavy weapons is not completed by that time, UN commanders on
the ground can ask Nato to carry out air strikes on Bosnian Serb positions.
In London, after a tense cabinet meeting at which several senior government
members warned against deeper British involvement in former Yugoslavia, Mr
Major announced that two companies of soldiers - about 300 in all - would be
redeployed from central Bosnia to Sarajevo.
Britain is also to send 60 troops with radar equipment to locate heavy
weaponry sited around the Bosnian capital, as well as up to 100 further
personnel.
In an implicit sideswipe against the US, which has no ground troops based in
former Yugoslavia, British ministers suggested that western nations which
have yet to contribute to the UN forces in Bosnia should meet the call from
General Sir Michael Rose, the UN commander, for an extra 3,000 troops.
Aid workers 'at risk' in Bosnia air strikes, Page 3
</TEXT>
