<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / International Company News: Electricite de France increases
profit by 24%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Electricite de France, the state-owned utility, shrugged off the effects of
recession to achieve net profits of FFr3.1bn (Dollars 526m) last year, an
increase of 24 per cent over 1992.
The results exclude a payment to the state, which is part of a four-year
agreement, and which is estimated at about FFr1bn for last year. Sales rose
by 3.5 per cent to FFr183.6bn, with a strong increase in exports of
electricity.
Mr Gilles Menage, chairman of EdF, said he expected only a slight increase
in electricity rates this year, of the order of 0.5 per cent, below an
expected inflation rate of just over 2 per cent. He described the limited
increase which has to be confirmed by Mr Edmond Alphandery, the economy
minister, as 'good news for the French consumer'.
Investments were held constant at FFr32.9bn, but the company's cashflow
strengthened and borrowings were reduced from FFr194.8bn to FFr176.5bn.
Interest costs represented about 9.5 per cent of turnover, according to EdF.
</TEXT>
