<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / International Company News: Austrian group aims to raise
Sch3bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK BLUM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VIENNA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mayr-Melnhof (MM), a family owned Austrian company and one of Europe's
leading carton and packaging companies, plans to raise about Sch3bn (Dollars
250m) through a share issue early in the spring, Mr Michael Groller, chief
board executive, said yesterday.
The Mayr-Melnhof family will keep a two-thirds stake after the flotation
which is expected to take place in April with Morgan Stanley as
international lead managers and Creditanstalt Bankverein, the Austrian bank,
as domestic managers. The shares will be offered to investors in western
Europe and the US, and will be listed on the Vienna Borse.
The proceeds will finance acquisitions in Europe. 'The industry is going
through a process of concentration. We have two options. We can either be a
local niche producer or build up our strength in Europe,' said Mr Alfred
Fogarassy, board member.
Past acquisitions financed from own resources included the purchase in 1992
of Deeside Paperbox in Manchester, UK, and a 50 per cent stake in CP Schmidt
Verpackungswerk of Germany. In addition to plants in Germany, the UK and
Austria, MM also has subsidiaries in Switzerland, France, Italy and the
Netherlands.
MM's activities in eastern Europe are expected to grow as part of its
strategy to supply multinational companies moving into new post-communist
markets. MM has a plant in Hungary, and projects are planned for Poland and
the Czech Republic.
MM was founded 100 years ago, and is one of the world's leading cardboard
manufacturers, producing carton board, folding cartons, and recycling waste
paper. In 1992, it produced about 1m tonnes of carton board, giving it a 20
per cent share of the European market. Production of folding carton used
primarily for packaging food, beverages, and other products such as washing
powders, was about 100,000 tonnes.
</TEXT>
