<DATE>940217
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / London Stock Exchange: BP slips
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, PETER JOHN and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Debate over whether or not the US is selling down its holding of British
Petroleum continued to overhang the UK traded shares. BP failed to benefit
from the general gains within the market and closed marginally lower at
366p.
The company said a shift of 3.6m shares out of the US over the course of
last week was minimal considering that it coincided with the company's
results.
However, at its morning meeting, stockbroker Nomura said the American
Depositary Receipt holding in BP had dropped by 1.4 percentage points to
25.9 per cent over the past four months and technical position-taking by
marketmakers meant the UK weighting could be substantially higher than the
74 per cent implied by the amount held in the form of ADRs. The conclusion
is that UK institutions have a less pressing need to pick up BP stock than
some might believe.
High street banks received support from James Capel, with National
Westminster the main beneficiary. The agency broker upgraded to buy from a
hold and raised its 1994 profits forecast by Pounds 140m to Pounds 1.455bn.
More significantly it has lifted its 1995 estimate by Pounds 269m to Pounds
1.859bn.
The house believes NatWest's exposure to small businesses in the south of
England will also be beneficial as economic recovery gathers pace. NatWest
shares rose 8 before closing a net 4 up at 559p, with turnover heavy at
7.5m.
Capel moved Abbey National to a buy from a hold and Barclays to a hold from
a sell. Abbey rose 9 to 522p, while Barclays was flat at 583p.
A Capel downgrade on HSBC was given further impetus by a weak Hong Kong
market. The broker lowered its predictions to 1994 profits of Pounds
2.687bn, against Pounds 2.93bn previously, and to 1995 profits of Pounds
3.085bn, against Pounds 3.40bn previously, bringing them back to the middle
of the range of analysts' estimates. HSBC fell 17 to 992p, while other Hong
Kong related stocks, Standard Chartered and Cable and Wireless, retreated 16
to 1285p and 9 to 483p respectively.
Merchant bank Kleinwort Benson fell 16 to 652p ahead of full-year figures
due today. Profits are expected to have at least doubled but the shares have
run up sharply.
Composite insurer General Accident recovered 21 to 681p after recent
underperformance. SGST reiterated its buy stance on the stock.
Insurance broker Willis Corroon was held back by US selling and dipped 6 to
209p.
Tobacco and insurance conglomerate BAT Industries slipped a penny to 497p
after an insurance company managed by Farmers, its US subsidiary, said it
would have to pay out about Pounds 400m in claims resulting from January's
Californian earthquake.
The release of the latest batch of retail sales figures provided inspiration
for a variety of moves among stores stocks. The dip in clothing and footwear
purchases was behind a retreat in Sears, off 1 1/2 at 121p, a lacklustre
showing by Next, up 2 at 226p, Stylo, stuck at 249p, and Austin Reed,
unchanged at 194p.
But better mixed retail sales, up 0.3 per cent in January, helped several
stocks, including Marks and Spencer, up 6 1/2 at 432 1/2 p. Great Universal
Stores climbed 7 to 609p, encouraged by the latest statistics and
underpinned by the current share buy-back story.
Increased prescription charges lifted Boots and Lloyds Chemists 7 to 543p
and 16 to 347p respectively.
However, Kingfisher remained a weak market, slipping 3 to 634p. The stock
has now declined 18 per cent in six weeks, as a bearish trading statement
was compounded by concern over Darty, the French electrical retailer. The
shares have been further unsettled by the resignation of Woolworth's
managing director over the weekend.
Independent oil and gas company Enterprise Oil eased 4 to 435p after NatWest
Securities reiterated a warning that continuing low crude oil prices would
make it difficult for the group to cover its dividend.
Television company Yorkshire Tyne Tees, which has been heated up by bid
speculation, came off the boil when some investors took profits and the
shares fell 28 to 336p.
Specialist engineering group James Wilkes, the subject of bid speculation in
recent sessions, declined 6 to 176p after saying it was not in talks with
stakeholder Suter, 2 ahead at 219p, or any other company. The conglomerate
last week increased its holding in Wilkes by 8.7 percentage points to 29.53
per cent. APV put on 3 at 130p, with SG Warburg said to have recommended the
stock.
British Airways brushed aside Tuesday's downgrades that followed the release
of third-quarter results. The shares bounced 6 to 479p. NatWest Securities
reiterated its buy recommendation, saying: 'Continued cost control combined
with rising load factors will result in rapid profits growth in future
years.'
Fears about the future of transport leasing group Tiphook saw the shares
lose 4 more to 54p.
Building and construction stocks were firm on the hope of interest rate cuts
and reports of strong mortgage demand in January. Bid talk added flavour to
the positive sentiment, with Wimpey, up 5 at 235p, mooted as a possible
target.
Building materials issues were strong, with Strauss Turnbull and UBS said to
be behind the rise of Redland, ahead 8 at 600p. Rugby Group added 7 at 338p
and Tarmac 8 at 194p, with Cazenove said to be pushing the latter.
</TEXT>
