<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / London Stock Exchange: BAe falls as Airbus loses deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, PETER JOHN and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
News that a Dollars 6bn Saudi Arabian aircraft order was to go to the US
rather than the Airbus consortium hit British Aerospace, which holds 20 per
cent of the European aircraft group.
The shares fell sharply early in the day, and anticipation of the US success
kept the stock in the doldrums before a mid-afternoon announcement from
President Clinton confirmed the order. Dealers said one US investment bank
was trying to sell a block of shares but finding no willing takers and that
was causing an additional drag on the share price.
However, late news that BAe's space division had been chosen as prime
contractor for a Pounds 300m project for two new defence satellites helped
the stock recover some of the earlier drop. The shares closed 9 off at 531p
after being 15 down at one stage.
Ironically, BAe is believed to be in talks about the sale of its space
division with Matra Marconi Space, one of the main subcontractors on the new
defence satellites, thought to be the most likely purchaser. A price of
between Pounds 40m and Pounds 50m has been suggested.
</TEXT>
