<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Renewed hopes of a reduction in UK interest rates following the release of a
mixed set of economic statistics kept stock index futures buoyant, writes
Joel Kibazo.
Having opened strongly at 3,396, the March contract on the FT-SE 100 Index
drifted for the first hour of trading as dealers awaited the 9.30am release
of economic data on retail price inflation, unemployment and retail sales
volume.
When they came, the statistics brought renewed speculation of a cut in
interest rates which sent dealers bidding for stock. A slight squeeze
occurred over the lunchtime period, as several of the big houses joined
independent traders as buyers of the contract.
A firm gilts sector, along with a positive start to trading on Wall Street,
gave a further boost to the contract, helping it to maintain a good premium
to cash for most of the day.
March finished at 3,414, up 24 from its previous close but around 3 points
below its fair value premium to cash of about minus 5. Volume at the
official close was 16,379 lots.
In traded options, there was strong business in the FT-SE 100 option, ahead
of tomorrow's expiry. A total of 42,417 contracts were dealt, of which
19,442 were in the FT-SE 100 option and 6,453 in the Euro FT-SE 100 option.
Abbey National topped the stock options with 2,573 lots traded.
</TEXT>
