<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow rise fades as inflation
data awaited
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices posted modest gains yesterday in a lacklustre session
highlighted by news of a Dollars 6bn contract for two US defence
contractors, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 9.00 up at 3,937.27, some way
below its session peak of 3,949.65. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 edged 0.27
higher to 472.79, while the Nasdaq composite added 2.50 at 792.62. Trading
volume on the New York SE was 295m shares.
Equities rose from the opening bell, thanks in part to the stability of the
dollar. After big losses earlier in the week tied to concern about the
possible outbreak of a trade war with Japan, the US currency held steady at
about Y103.80 yesterday. Bonds, which had also been rattled by the trade
dispute, were similarly becalmed, with the benchmark 30-year government
issue showing little change on the day.
Activity in the bond market was listless as traders awaited today's
all-important inflation data. Analysts expect the January consumer price
index to show a gain of about 0.3 per cent. Anything below that should boost
share prices, but if consumer prices are seen to have moved substantially
higher last month, fears that the Federal Reserve might put up short-term
interest rates would resurface.
It was concern about that possibility which kept some equity investors on
the sidelines yesterday, and limited the stock market's advance.
The biggest development of the day was the announcement that McDonnell
Douglas and Boeing would split a Dollars 6bn order for commercial jets from
Saudi Arabia. Boeing climbed Dollars 2 to Dollars 46 1/2 on the news. The
stock also benefited from Tuesday's announcement from the aircraft
manufacturer that it planned to increase its monthly production of 767s.
McDonnell Douglas, meanwhile, rose Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 118 7/8 .
Hewlett-Packard was another of the session's stars, advancing Dollars 3 5/8
to Dollars 89 1/8 in volume of 2.6m shares after the computer manufacturer
announced fiscal first-quarter net income of Dollars 368m, up from Dollars
261m a year earlier.
The good news from Hewlett-Packard lifted other technology stocks.
Motorola surged Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars 104 1/2 in the wake of US threats
to impose trade sanctions on Japan if Tokyo refused to give better market
access to the company's cellular telephones.
Many of the best performing blue chip issues in recent weeks had strong
outings. 3M was Dollars 1 1/8 higher at Dollars 109 1/2 , Alcoa advanced
Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 79 5/8 and United Technologies climbed Dollars 2
5/8 to Dollars 71.
On the Nasdaq market, QVC continued to rise following its defeat in the
Paramount bid battle, adding Dollars 1 1/4 at Dollars 51 1/2 .
Canada
Toronto received a late boost from a recovery in the precious metals
sub-sector and ended a sluggish session mildly firmer.
An analyst said there were 'spotty areas of strength elsewhere - forest
products, base metals - but the market is still showing some signs of
hesitancy going into February 22' (the budget).
The TSE 300 index gained 9.7 at 4,424.1. Turnover was 67.37m shares valued
at CDollars 774m and rises and falls were almost equal at 406 to 405.
</TEXT>
