<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / World Stock Markets (Asia Pacific): Region volatile, mostly
on downside as Nikkei firms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A lull in the yen's ascent against the dollar prompted bargain hunting and
the Nikkei 225 average gained moderate ground, writes Emiko Terazono in
Tokyo.
The 225 index climbed above the 19,000 level again, ending with an advance
of 77.51 at 19,052.11 after a day's high of 19,267.03 and low of 19,032.40
just before the close.
Dealers led the way as participants bought to adjust their positions, and
this pushed equities up in the morning session as the dollar strengthened
against the Japanese currency.
Continued dollar buying by the Bank of Japan in the foreign exchange market
also encouraged some investors. The Topix index of all first section stocks
firmed 3.76 to 1,559.10, although the Nikkei 300 capitalisation weighted
index lost 0.05 at 287.65.
Traders said reports of North Korea's decision to accept international
inspection of its nuclear power sites also supported investor confidence.
However, many investors, remaining wary of currency fluctuations due to
lingering concern over US-Japan trade tensions, were still absent.
Volume totalled 360m shares, against Tuesday's 389m. Rising issues
outnumbered declines by 770 to 265, with 136 stocks unchanged. In London the
ISE/Nikkei 50 index put on 1.43 at 1,288.56.
Speculative trading by indvidual investors led activity. Shindengen
Electric, the leader in volume terms, closed a net Y30 off at Y1,140. The
issue has been actively bought recently on rumours of purchases by
speculative investors, and was higher in the morning session yesterday on
reports of better than expected profits for the current year.
Domestic investors bought Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, which rose Y3,000
to Y898,000. East Japan Railway gained Y8,000 at Y492,000.
Some export related stocks recovered, having lost ground previously on fears
of lower profits due to the rise in the yen. Fujitsu moved ahead Y13 to Y991
and Hitachi firmed Y5 to Y875. However, Sony finally lost Y10 at Y5,860 in
spite of initial strength, and NEC declined Y14 to Y971.
Some financials were lower on profit-taking. Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank shed Y10
to Y1,920 and Sumitomo Bank declined Y40 to Y2,110, while Tokio Marine and
Fire, the non-life insurer, fell Y20 to Y1,280.
In Osaka, the OSE average rose 190.02 to 21,215.83 in volume of 55.7m
shares.
Roundup
There was widespread volatility in the region, with most of it on the
downside.
HONG KONG shelved UK-based recovery hopes after an early attempt to indulge
them, the Hang Seng index tumbling 378.19, or 3.4 per cent, to 10,634.14
after an initial high of 11,119.51. Turnover remained modest, at HKDollars
6.14bn.
Brokers blamed selling from the US, and by British business interests.
Sellers talked of an expected rise in interest rates tomorrow as HSBC slid
HKDollars 2 to HKDollars 115. Conglomerates led the retreat, however,
Hutchison slipping HKDollars 2.25 to HKDollars 34.50, Jardine Matheson
HKDollars 3.50 to HKDollars 72 and Swire 'A' HKDollars 4 to HKDollars 57.50.
TAIWAN also reversed early gains, ending 2 per cent lower as late selling
focused on the weak financial sector. The weighted index opened 100 points
up, but closed 122.38 down at 5,862.63. Turnover was moderate at TDollars
58.3bn.
Taiwan has its own trade talks with the US next week, and investors have
also been worried about the central bank's interest rate policy.
JAKARTA extended Tuesday's falls, the composite index ending 7.89, or 1.35
per cent, lower at 574.82. Bank International Indonesia dropped by 17.4 per
cent to Rp7,025 in thin volume, dealers saying that restrictions on foreign
ownership might be affecting the domestic market.
BOMBAY weakened after a dull opening led funds and institutions into
selling, the BSE index losing a further 92.71, or 2.3 per cent, at 3,807.42.
Brokers said foreign institutional investors, who fuelled a bull run between
November and January, have cut back on their purchases after facing problems
over share deliveries.
KARACHI saw early buying interest take flight after reports of possible
unrest in the north west frontier province, the KSE 100 index surrendering
21.47 at 2,401.52.
SEOUL said sentiment improved on North Korea's decision to accept
international inspection of its nuclear sites. The composite index finished
18.62, or 2.1 per cent, ahead at 920.43.
North Korea agreed on Tuesday to allow inspectors from the International
Atomic Energy Agency to check seven declared nuclear plants in the hardline
communist state.
AUSTRALIA gained on the advances in the US and Japan, the All Ordinaries
index closing 15.0 higher at 2,249.0. Resource issues improved, Western
Mining climbing 19 cents to ADollars 7.61 on its partnership in a
'technically feasible' gas discovery.
SINGAPORE saw revived interest in over-the-counter trading in Malaysian
shares. Meanwhile, the Straits Times Industrial index rose 11.85 to
2,341.38, with Rothmans Industries up SDollars 1.15 at SDollars 9.30 on news
of a special dividend.
