<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / World Stock Markets: Latin America reflects flow of funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN PITT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Latin America has been benefiting over recent weeks from a general movement
of institutional money out of Asia.
This is clearly indicated by a 20 per cent rise in dollar terms since the
start of the year, compared to an 11 per cent fall in Asia. The European
markets have been hit even harder, dropping by some 20 per cent since
January, although here the story has been influenced by a steep decline in
Turkey.
On a summary inspection, Brazil stands out as the clear leader in Latin
America this year. But, says Mr Roger Palmer of Kleinwort Benson in London,
since last November all of the markets in the region have performed in a
broadly similar manner, with rises of between 42 to 52 per cent in dollar
terms.
While investors have been encouraged by progress in balancing the Brazilian
budget, it is still too early, says Mr Palmer, to view the country's
economic difficulties as all but solved. A lot depends on whether the
introduction of a new index designed to tackle inflation will make a
significant impression. He takes the view that this is far from certain,
especially because of the fluid political situation, with elections due
later this year.
Sri Lanka has been showing solid performance in south Asia, with investors
attracted by its relative cheapness, compared with India. Ms Susan Murphy of
Smith New Court comments that the launch of new country funds has helped.
