<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Co-operative spirit fades as
world bauxite prices languish - Canute James talks to the president of the
industry association
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CANUTE JAMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Producers of bauxite have reacted with disappointment to the US's decision
to reduce its strategic stockpile of the aluminium ore, which it has built
up since the early 1960s.
Mr Nenad Altman, secretary-general of the International Bauxite Association,
warns that the move will affect all bauxite producers in an industry already
depressed by falling demand because of the weak international aluminium
market.
'It is not just the quantity which is being sold, which is about 3m tonnes
over two years,' Mr Altman says. 'Producers are also being affected by the
price, which is about Dollars 8.50 per tonne. This will push prices further
down. It is a small proportion of world production but the psychological
impact on the market will be severe.'
The waning fortunes of the world's bauxite producers have coincided with
some soul-searching among the IBA's members and within the organisation.
When the association was created 20 years ago, metals companies were worried
that it would attempt to build an industry cartel - some even made highly
unrealistic comparisons to the Organisation of Petroleum Exporting
Countries. But the IBA has steered clear of such activity, acting primarily
a data bank and forum for its members.
In better times the association's members have accounted for about 85 per
cent of the western world's bauxite production, while contributing 54 per
cent of alumina (aluminium oxide) production and 18 per cent of primary
aluminium output. The loss of two founding members - the Dominican Republic
and Haiti - in the 1980s, because their industries folded, had no effect on
the IBA. But Australia'a decision two years ago not to renew its membership
seriously reduced the organisation's weight and influence. Australia is the
world's largest bauxite producer.
'Given the state of the market and the problems facing bauxite producers,
now is the time they should be getting closer together to defend their
common interests,' says a representative of the Jamaican industry. 'But this
is not happening. There appears to be less interest now in the IBA, even
among some members which have been delinquent in meeting their financial
obligations to the organisation.'
With members' financial support to the IBA based on volume of production,
Australia's departure deprived the association of 40 per cent of its budget.
'This has inevitably affected the association's budget,' says Mr Altman.
'The majority of the member countries are facing financial difficulties, and
so we could not operate as before because of a reduced budget.'
There seems to be little enthusiasm among the world's major producers to
join the IBA. Attempts to recruit Brazil only led to the country adopting
observer status.
Expansion may have to await to resolution of a political conundrum. The
association lists its members as Ghana, Guinea, Guyana, India, Indonesia,
Jamaica, Sierra Leone and Surinam, but also Yugoslavia, which no longer
exists. 'The IBA is willing to extend membership to all parts of the
previous Yugoslavia if they wish to continue,' says the secretary-general.
'There is bauxite in Bosnia, Croatia, Montenegro and Serbia, but the major
producer is Bosnia.'
Contributing to the IBA's relatively low profile has been its inability to
negotiate a commodity pact between bauxite producers and consumers under the
aegis of the United Nations Committee on Trade and Development. The attempt
was abandoned because of lack of support from either side, and because
bauxite could not be organised in pacts similar to those for other
commodities such as cocoa and coffee, Mr Altman explains.
'There is now an attempt to find common ground for a forum of producers and
consumers - a loose body to discuss the state of the industry,' he says.
'This would involve all three levels of the industry - bauxite, alumina and
aluminium. There have been ad hoc meetings to see if such a forum can be
established. . . but there is still reluctance by some to be part of this.'
However, the IBA secretary-general maintains that the association's main
role is to provide its members with information on the industry - a role
that is increasingly important when the market is languishing. Bauxite
producers are 'between a rock and a hard place', he says, and have to decide
whether it is better to sell more ore at lower prices or less at higher
prices. And he warns that ore producers have no basis on which to anticipate
an improvement in the market over the next two years.
'These factors are not within the direct influence of bauxite producers,' Mr
Altman admits. 'What they need is a healthy economic recovery in the
industrialised countries. The market is now heavily oversupplied and any
hopes for a significant increase in consumption to soak up the surplus will
not be realised soon.'
