<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / International Company News: Turnround at Enso-Gutzeit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Enso-Gutzeit, the Finnish pulp and paper group, has put two years of losses
behind it by posting a FM385m (Dollars 70m) profit after financial items for
1993.
The result, which compares with a FM192m deficit in 1992 and a FM950m loss
in 1991, was struck after a 27 per cent jump in net sales to FM13.06bn.
Mr Jukka Harmala, chief executive, attributed the improvement to
cost-cutting, the weaker Finnish markka, higher productivity and lower wood
prices. He noted all the group's divisions had produced better figures in
markka terms, in spite of difficult market conditions throughout the pulp
and paper industry.
The strong growth in sales reflected markka weakness and the group's
expansion programme. It acquired Tampella's forest products and packaging
operations for FM3.6bn in May. It benefited from increased sales from its
new Enocell pulp mill. The group partly offset weakness in European markets
by increasing sales to south-east Asia.
Analysts believe the result may encourage the government to reduce its
majority stake in Enso as part of the long-awaited launch of its
privatisation programme.
The group's consolidated operating margin amounted to FM2.99bn, or 22.9 per
cent of net sales, up seven percentage points on 1992. Depreciation rose to
FM1.1bn from FM786m, and net interest expenses increased to FM1.38bn from
FM955m.
Exchange rate losses at FM140m were FM60m higher than in 1992.
</TEXT>
