<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Auditors voice disquiet over HunterPrint
debt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in HunterPrint, the specialist printing group, lost 20 per cent of
their value yesterday after its auditors expressed 'fundamental uncertainty'
over the going concern assumption used in the accounts.
The shares closed down 4p at 16p after BDO Binder Hamlyn said: 'The group
meets its day to day working capital requirements through its overdraft
facility, which at the year end was substantially utilised.
'There is a material level of concern as to the appropriateness of the going
concern basis.'
In the 12 months to September 26 last year, the group incurred a deficit of
Pounds 3.2m before tax, compared with a restated loss of Pounds 12.2m in
1992.
Despite the apparent improvement, the auditors are understood to have
expressed disquiet at the group's growing borrowing requirement.
HunterPrint last year increased its bank overdraft to Pounds 8.9m from a
restated Pounds 3.4m, while at the same maintaining a Pounds 6m loan secured
against its Corby factory.
Although Barclays, the group's banker, has extended financing facilities to
September 30 this year, the loans are repayable on demand.
Mr Geoff Eades, finance director, admitted net borrowings of Pounds 17.9m
(Pounds 9.6m) were higher than expected, but said institutional shareholders
remained fully behind the group.
He said gearing had exceeded forecast levels because the group spent Pounds
6.2m on plant and facilities, including three second-hand presses.
The presses were purchased to ensure capacity for new printing contracts
with Associated Newspapers, Mirror Group Newspapers and the Guardian Media
Group, worth a combined total of Pounds 10m a year.
HunterPrint was also pursuing a cost-cutting programme expected to save
Pounds 3m, Mr Eades added.
'Wages and salaries have been cut by 10 per cent, and we will be looking for
further savings,' he said.
Large institutional shareholders, including M&amp;G, Fidelity and Standard Life,
said yesterday they were aware of the situation and welcomed moves by the
group to cut spending.
