<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Great Western Resources seeking Pounds 15m
investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Great Western Resources, the restructured energy group that almost collapsed
in a fog of litigation more than two years ago, yesterday called on
investors for support with a Pounds 15m placing and open offer.
GWR is also planning to float in the US before the end of the year. The
company was one of several US-based energy companies to float in the UK
during the so-called 'gas bubble' of the 1980s.
Existing investors are being offered one share at 38p for every four held.
GWR is issuing a total of 40.9m shares, leaving an enlarged equity base of
126m. Some 72 per cent of the new shares have been placed with institutions.
GWR said it was confident that it had 'effectively dealt with the immediate
problems'. Funds were now needed to allow it to 'plan for the development of
the company'.
The group, under previous management, ran into difficulties when one of its
largest customers suspended payments after a dispute over contracts. It was
also the focus of unwelcome publicity over its controversial former chairman
and founder, Mr Dan Pena. Mr Pena, whose financial transactions with the
company prompted a rebellion by institutional shareholders and pressure for
his departure, last year won a claim for unfair dismissal.
Mr Gary Loveless, chief executive, said the proceeds of the placing and open
offer would be used to develop GWR's oil and gas assets in the US and to
invest in exploration in Peru.
Last year, GWR was awarded an exploration agreement in the Manon Basin by
Petroperu. Mr Loveless said the group intended to seek a partner to help
develop the bloc.
The exploration asset had been a particular attraction for institutions
participating in the placing, Mr Loveless said. All of the placed funds had
been raised through UK institutions, two of which were first-time investors
in GWR.
Some 10 per cent of the proceeds would be used to reduce debt, leaving
borrowings at about Dollars 62m. A refinancing agreement negotiated in 1992,
after the company breached several banking covenants, specifies that 10 per
cent of any equity issue be used to reduce debt. Before the issue the group
had gearing of about 65 per cent.
</TEXT>
