FT  17 FEB 94 / UK Company News: TDG quits Australia and plans expansion of
core activities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Transport Development Group has agreed to sell Transic and its Australian
subsidiary companies to Jamison Equity for Pounds 21.5m cash.
The proceeds will be used to expand TDG's European activities operating in
the core business areas of distribution, storage, transport and hire. The
withdrawal from Australia marked a further step in the group's stated
objective of being a first choice European logistics group.
The Australian companies are principally engaged in providing storage,
distribution and transport services on Australia's eastern and southern
seaboards.
Jamison, an Australian company with interests in manufacturing, retailing,
private medical services and stevedoring, intends to manage the companies
under their present names.
The Australian companies made pre-tax profits of Pounds 900,000 before group
finance charges in 1992, and had net assets of Pounds 20.9m.
Harris Distribution, a division of TDG, has lost out in its bid for the
contract to build and operate a distribution centre for Mars Confectionery.
The new facility, which will not be fully operational until late 1995 or
early 1996, will replace two Harris warehouses currently dedicated to Mars
business, at Elmdon, near Birmingham, and Heywood, near Manchester. The
group said contractual arrangements with Mars include compensation for the
possible closure of the two warehouses, which have combined annual revenues
of about Pounds 5.4m.
