<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / GKN bid 'threatens Westland strategy'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Westland, the helicopter manufacturer, yesterday warned that moves to
restructure the company and forge overseas alliances could be undermined if
the engineering group GKN succeeded with its hostile bid.
Mr Alan Jones, Westland chief executive, said the future of the Yeovil-based
manufacturer would not be enhanced either in management techniques or
military sales if GKN, which already manufactures armoured vehicles, won
full control.
The engineering and industrial services group launched a bid for Westland
last week after agreeing to lift its 28.3 per cent stake by acquiring 18.7
per cent held by United Technologies, the US parent of Sikorsky helicopters.
GKN, which has a 45 per cent stake in Westland on a fully diluted basis, has
offered remaining shareholders 290p per ordinary and preferred share, 354.8p
for each convertible preferred share and 208.3p for each warrant, all
payable in cash with a partial share alternative. It is expected to post its
formal offer document in the next few days.
Stepping up his opposition to the bid, Mr Jones said: 'Our managers are
encouraged to run the company with vision and courage. I'm not sure GKN can
continue that.'
He is expected to tell Westland shareholders at today's annual general
meeting, when he will take over as chairman, that the company is well placed
to win new orders in partnership with overseas manufacturers such as
McDonnell Douglas of the US and Agusta of Italy.
Mr Jones, who met Agusta executives in Italy on Tuesday, said: 'We have a
strong relationship and they want to stay with the people they know. We also
have a deal running with McDonnell Douglas. GKN would not augment our
ability to continue with such collaborators.'
The engineering company declined to respond yesterday.
Mr Jones, meanwhile, said Westland's two largest institutional shareholders
 -M&amp;G and Schroders - have reaffirmed their opposition to GKN's offer.
'They know the real value of the company is much more than 290p (a share).
Shareholders should stay on board to get the upside when we turn orders into
deliveries.'
Westland shares closed unchanged at 333p, a 14.8 per cent premium to the GKN
offer.
