<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / Greece cuts Macedonia trade link in dispute over name and
flag
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Greece said yesterday it was suspending diplomatic ties with Macedonia and
would no longer permit the former Yugoslav republic to import fuel and other
goods through the northern Greek port of Thessaloniki.
Mr Andreas Papandreou, the Greek prime minister, made the announcement live
on television before the start of a cabinet meeting, adding that 'Greece is
forced to make its position clear with specific actions'.
The move came in response to domestic criticism of the Socialist government
for failing to wring concessions out of Macedonia in the dispute over its
name and use of an ancient Greek symbol, the Vergina star, on its flag.
Yesterday European Commission officials in Brussels were holding intensive
talks in an attempt to find a way of defusing the crisis. Greece currently
holds the rotating presidency of the European Union and its action is likely
to embarrass EU partners.
The Greek government was put out when the US followed EU member states in
granting official recognition to Macedonia last week.
The decision to deny Macedonian companies access to Thessaloniki could have
a serious impact on the Macedonian economy, already hit by UN sanctions on
neighbouring Serbia.
Mr Papandreou is under attack from his party's radical wing for not opposing
more strongly Nato's air strike ultimatum to Bosnian Serbs. Mr Carolos
Papoulias, foreign minister, visited Belgrade this week to reassure
President Slobodan Milosevic that Greece would not weaken its relationship
with Serbia.
In the Macedonian capital of Skopje, the Macedonian foreign ministry said it
had been informed that the Greek consulate was being closed and staff
withdrawn. Mr Papandreou spoke of a decision to 'suspend the activities of
its consulate in Skopje', leaving the exact status of relations uncertain.
In order to answer Greek claims that Macedonia's name implies a territorial
claim on the Greek province of the same name, Mr Kiro Gligorov, the
Macedonian president, has offered to sign an agreement guaranteeing the
border.
</TEXT>
