<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ITV begins two new series. The Big Race records an overland car race from
London to New York, the first leg taking the contestants to Moscow.
Highlights, we are promised, include a journey through the Channel Tunnel
and New Year's Eve in Minsk (7.30). Commando is yet another of those series
that make you glad you never became a soldier. Just as every country
believes it makes the best chocolate and the best knives, so every
specialised military unit in the world believes its training course is the
toughest. This series follows two troops of men hoping to become British
Commandos (9.30).
BBC1's new half-hour sitcom Nelson's Column is set in the offices of a local
newspaper. Gavin Nelson (hence the title; if you think national papers are
too fond of puns just look at some of the provincials) pursues local
scandals and the office junior, Clare, with equal enthusiasm (8.00).
Secret History offers a story about a racial purity programme in the US
which sounds chilling, starting in the 1920s and not abandoned until 1972
(9.00 C4).
</TEXT>
