<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / Value of jobless data questioned: Department of Employment
statistics under fire
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Political debate resumed yesterday over the meaning of Britain's official
monthly unemployment figures.
Mr John Prescott, Labour's employment spokesman, for once refused to comment
on the rise in registered jobless. 'Whether the total out of work goes up or
down, I am no longer going to take part in a sterile debate about statistics
that are irrelevant to unemployment,' he said. He added that the monthly
count of the number of jobless people claiming unemployment-related benefit
was 'not a true measure of unemployment'.
Mr Prescott said the claimant count understated the jobless total by about
30 per cent.
Mr Prescott is due to meet Mr Peter Stibbard, head of the Department of
Employment's statistical services, to discuss how the unemployment figures
are compiled. Mr Prescott said he hoped this could lead to agreement with
the government on 'a proper measure of unemployment'.
The government estimates that its new jobseeker's allowance to replace
unemployment benefit in the spring of 1996 will cut the monthly overall
jobless figure by up to 90,000.
Mr Prescott would like to replace the present monthly benefit headcount as
the basis for the jobless total with the assessment based on a controlled
sample of households, currently used in the government's quarterly labour
force survey.
People without work in the labour force survey sample are asked if they want
a job, whether they have looked for one in the previous four weeks and if
they ready to start work the next week.
The latest quarterly figure based on those questions showed there were
2.894m people jobless in the second quarter of last year. This compared with
an average total of 2.811m unemployed for the same period compiled from the
benefit claimants.
As Mr Paul Convery of the independent Unemployment Unit pointed out
yesterday, however, the difference between the two figures varies
dramatically.
He said: 'The labour force survey figures are very sensitive to people's
perceptions of the labour market.'
The existing benefit count system costs Pounds 1m a year and the quarterly
labour force survey Pounds 6m a year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
