<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / Rail track charges attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The high level of charges to be levied on train operators for the use of
track could discourage some teams of British Rail managers from making
buy-outs bids, it emerged yesterday.
Steep increases from the charges now levied by BR will push some profitable
parts of the system into loss and make them dependent on considerable levels
of subsidy. Although the government has promised to increase subsidies in
line with higher track charges the result will damage management morale.
One manager said: 'We would become a subsidised route. We are concerned
about the impact on staff morale and on the negative message this will send
to the outside world. We won't have the bulk of our costs under our own
control. We would be happier to earn our revenues from ticket sales than
from the government.'
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, said when announcing the increased
track charges on Tuesday that they were 50 per cent higher than the amounts
charged internally by BR. The 24 rail operating companies can expect to pay
about Pounds 2.2bn for use of the track.
Some rail managers believe the increases for particular lines will be much
higher, amounting to a doubling or trebling of charges.
Other potential bidders for rail franchises said that until they were able
to discuss the charges to be levied by Railtrack, which will take over BR's
track and signalling from April 1, they would not be able to assess the
impact on their operations.
Some were hopeful that they would be able to negotiate lower charges from
Railtrack, which has said that it will make refinements to its calculations
in the next few months.
The government has presented the increased track charges as an accounting
exercise which will not have any impact in the real world.
But, one industry observer said, the rail operating companies would be
required to make profits and pay dividends to their shareholders, which
would result in funds being syphoned out of the railway.
Gatwick Express, which is likely to be the first of BR's operations to be
sold off, took a more positive view of the publication of track charges. The
Pounds 8m track charge allocated to the Gatwick service was in line with the
amount the company had been expecting.
Gatwick Express said it had not yet decided whether to apply for a subsidy.
'Other costings still have to come in but we believe we can break even,' it
said. 'If we do require a subsidy we will be bidding for the lowest
possible.'
Rail managers said they were also concerned that by becoming more dependent
on government funds they would be vulnerable to cuts in subsidies that might
be decided in future.
One said that the government appeared intent on making Railtrack and other
parts of the rail industry profitable but keeping the train-operating
companies dependent on subsidy.
</TEXT>
