<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / Labour starts offensive over nursery places
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour went on the offensive over the government's record on nursery
education yesterday by publishing figures which showed that
Labour-controlled councils provided three times more nursery places than
Conservative authorities.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, said last year that he wanted universal
nursery education. But Mrs Ann Taylor, shadow education secretary, said
there was a deep split over the issue between Mr Major and Mr John Patten,
the education secretary.
She said: 'The secretary of state still clings stubbornly to the belief that
child care, valuable though that may be for working parents, can be a
substitute for proper nursery education for children. That is nonsense.'
Mrs Taylor's attack signalled that nursery education will be one of Labour's
main issues in May's local government elections.
The figures, compiled by the Department for Education, show that 34 of the
40 local education authorities in England with the highest proportions of
three and four-year-olds in nursery education are Labour-controlled. None of
the bottom 25 is Labour-controlled.
Newham, a Labour-controlled east London borough, came highest with 64 per
cent, followed by Walsall (where no party has overall control) on 60 per
cent, and the Labour councils of Cleveland, Manchester, Merton and Sandwell
on 57 per cent. Gloucestershire (no overall control) had no nursery
education.
Mr Patten yesterday announced the first eight schools to be given approval
to set up sixth forms under a new government initiative in response to the
'staying-on revolution'.
</TEXT>
