<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / Barclays rapped over man's suicide
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A widow said yesterday that she was considering suing Barclays Bank after an
inquest returned a verdict of suicide on her husband.
Stephen Langley killed himself after Barclays Bank demanded the return of
his cheque book and card because making a loan repayment would have made his
account overdrawn by Pounds 72, Birmingham coroners court heard.
The inquest hear that his monthly wage of Pounds 943 had not been credited
to his Coventry account because of a delay in the clearing system. 'Mr
Langley was harried in a way quite unsuitable in the circumstances for a
comparatively small amount of money,' said Mr Richard Whittington, the
coroner. He had been depressed before and the bank's letters may have tipped
the balance.
The inquest heard that Mr Langley had struggled to repay several previous
instalments of the Pounds 1,200 loan and had pledged to remain in credit
after bank counselling.
Barclays said: 'Knowing what we know, we believe we acted as sympathetically
as possible in the circumstances and given the same situation again we would
do the same.'
</TEXT>
