<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / Investment body announces board
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Personal Investment Authority, the planned new watchdog for retail
financial services, yesterday announced the final composition of its board,
which is to increase from 19 members to 21.
This does not mean, however, that the authority has bowed to pressure from
within the financial services industry that current practitioners should
form a majority on the board. The board will have 10 practitioners, with 10
public-interest directors, including the chairman and the chief executive.
The announcement on the board's composition settles one of the remaining
questions before publication of the authority's prospectus next Monday,
assuming that the Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief
watchdog, gives approval today.
The industry will use the prospectus, and more detailed information on how
the authority plans to approach regulation, to decide whether to support the
new regulator.
Only one public-interest director remains to be appointed.
The four new practitioner directors are: Mr Lawrence Churchill (National
Westminster Life Assurance); Mr Peter Gray (Tunbridge Wells Equitable
Friendly Society); Mr Geoffrey Lister (Bradford &amp; Bingley building society);
and Mr Michael Pickard (Royal London Insurance).
</TEXT>
