<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / Tory chiefs aim to heal splits in party
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Conservative managers plan a drive to rally the party behind Mr John Major
before a triple campaign for local, parliamentary and European elections
starts in earnest.
Party strategists are concerned that the political fall-out from Mr Major's
troubled Back to Basics initiative is being compounded by a festering split
on Europe.
They fear that internal divisions could undermine hopes of avoiding
humiliation in the local elections, three Commons by-elections in May and
the European poll in June.
Mr Major was given a significant boost last night by Mr Peter Lilley, social
security secretary, in a speech to the rightwing 92 Group of Conservative
MPs. His speech, to an audience which has frequently been hostile to Mr
Major, amounted to an attempt to dispel suggestions that cabinet
rightwingers were not giving Mr Major full support.
Mr Lilley praised the 'clarity' of the prime minister's views on Europe and
insisted that Mr Major was 'the only person who can lead a united party to
victory in the next general election'.
Party officials are concerned, however, that a split on federalism may burst
into the open next week when the European People's party publishes its
European election manifesto.
Tory strategists plan to use speeches by cabinet ministers at the weekend to
distance the party from the federalist EPP, which includes several
conservative delegations in the European parliament.
The speeches will stress that the EPP manifesto is not binding on
Conservative candidates in an attempt to forestall criticism from rightwing
Euro-sceptics such as Lord Tebbit.
Officials say the intention is to link Britain's sustained economic recovery
to the opt-out which Mr Major secured from the social chapter of the
Maastricht treaty.
The prime minister is expected to stress the need for party unity during the
second of a series of regional tours - a two-day visit to Scotland starting
tonight.
On his return from Moscow last night Mr Major was presented with a difficult
decision on whether to fight rebel Conservative peers who have virtually
wrecked the government's controversial police bill.
An escalation of the row over parliamentary business was headed off
yesterday when Tory MPs on the Commons trade and industry committee decided
against pressing ahead immediately with their threatened coup against Mr
Richard Caborn, the committee's Labour chairman.
The MPs - who form a majority on the committee - passed a motion giving Mr
Caborn a two-week stay.
They expect him to use this period to take 'appropriate steps' to halt what
they regard as 'unacceptable interference' with the committee's freedom of
action.
Mr Caborn said last night he would make 'appropriate representations' to
carry out the terms of the resolution.
</TEXT>
<XX>
