<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / Interest but few takers in multi-media markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is widespread corporate interest in the multi-media market but not
many companies are ready to take advantage of the new business
opportunities, says an international survey.
Formerly separate sectors such as computers, telecommunications,
broadcasting and entertainment are covered by multi-media.
More than 500 executives from cable and satellite companies throughout
Europe and North America responded to a detailed questionnaire devised by
consultants Touche Ross in co-operation with the Financial Times.
The survey shows that while 89 per cent were interested in multi-media
markets and in offering multi-media services, only 33 per cent were ready to
move.
In the consumer market the services seen as most likely to be successful
within the next three or four years ranged from computer games and
video-on-demand to screen-based home shopping.
A little further down the consumer market line, screen-based distance
learning and home banking were seen as potential growth services.
In the business sector, on-line business and financial news, company
messaging, interactive travel information and booking and computer-based
training were judged the services most likely to succeed in the next four
years.
Nearly 90 per cent of respondents supported the view that co-ventures and
collaboration across several industries would be needed to encourage market
development.
Mr Rob Woodward, telecommunications and media partner at Touche Ross, warned
of multi-media hype at yesterday's FT Cable and Satellite conference and
said the pace of market development may have been exaggerated.
'It's not yet a revolution,' he warned.
A full report on the survey will be published next month.
</TEXT>
<XX>
