<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / Bottomley hits at ineffective NHS surgery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hospital doctors carry out too many operations that are clinically
ineffective and cause unnecessary costs to the National Health Service, Mrs
Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, will say today.
Mrs Bottomley, in a speech to be delivered to a conference in Birmingham,
will launch a campaign to ensure that more operations are driven by 'fact
not fashion'. She will also argue that new research and development
techniques need to be applied systematically to the whole of the NHS.
According to Mrs Bottomley the prevailing view on the necessity for some
operations has changed, and the NHS needs to concentrate money on activities
that bring the most benefit.
In an advance copy of the speech she calls into question the method of
treating 'glue ear' - the illness that was at the heart of a political storm
in the last general election campaign, when a girl called 'Jennifer' was
highlighted as having failed to receive treatment quickly enough.
Mrs Bottomley supports the view that 'the optimal medical treatment for
Jennifer might well have been to wait'.
The health secretary also claims that old-fashioned methods may sometimes
bring surprising results in treatment. She asks: 'Who would have thought
that the humble leech, passed over by the age of reason and science, would
be making a comeback as part of the plastic surgeon's repertoire of
micro-surgical techniques?'
Mrs Bottomley says that managers 'do have a proper role keeping up the
pressure by reminding clinicians that when a decision is made, a cheque is
written'.
She also calls for patients to be involved more fully in the decisions over
whether an operation should be carried out. 'The patient, who has to live
with the consequences, has a right to be involved in these dilemmas.' Mrs
Bottomley outlines three ways in which clinical effectiveness could be
raised:
Using research to find out what works and to evaluate costs. Using
education, clinical guidelines and contracts between purchasers and
providers to promote what works.
Using clinical audit to assess the effectiveness of what is done.
</TEXT>
<XX>
