<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / Loyalists issue a call to arms: Michael Cassell on the
motives behind the violent campaign against nationalists in Ulster
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This week's Valentine's day chocolate-box bomb attacks on Northern Ireland's
Roman Catholic community have heightened fears in the security forces that
the province faces a rising wave of loyalist paramilitary violence.
With IRA terrorist activity at a lower level during the lengthening
republican debate on the Downing Street declaration, loyalist attacks have
been at the forefront of violence in Ulster and have triggered arguments
over motives behind the escalating campaign.
The recent attacks, which have left three people dead and several badly
injured, have also provoked a fresh row among Ulster's political parties.
Some nationalists say unionist attempts to explain the upsurge in loyalist
extremism are fanning the flames of hatred. The Royal Ulster Constabulary is
once again the target of allegations of suspected collusion between officers
and loyalist paramilitaries.
Loyalists who have traditionally claimed their attacks are in direct
response to IRA violence and would stop if the IRA laid down its arms, now
insist they are fighting to halt what they see as the political assault on
the province's position within the Union. The struggle to stop a looming
'sell-out' to Sinn Fein has, apparently, joined hatred of the IRA and
impatience with the security forces' efforts as a legitimate motive for
their activities.
The loyalist onslaught has involved attacks with guns, bombs and mortars.
Sinn Fein headquarters and nationalist politicians have been targets and
attacks on Catholics have occurred. Most of the incidents have been claimed
by the Ulster Freedom Fighters, an arm of the Ulster Defence Association,
the province's largest paramilitary group.
Dr Philip McGarry, chairman of the centre Alliance party, says the UFF
campaign means 'any Catholic is now a target of the loyalists'. Mr Seamus
Mallon, deputy leader of the mainly nationalist Social Democratic and Labour
party, believes the paramilitaries are now intent upon killing his party
members.
Some Ulster politicians believe the loyalists' latest explanation for their
activities is no more than a smokescreen for continuing sectarian warfare.
But a UDA statement after the weekend murder attempt on a leading SDLP
member said it was part of its 'on-going proactive campaign against those
directly involved in exercising the nationalist veto on democratic progress
within Northern Ireland'.
Unionists have been criticised for talking about a 'pan-nationalist' front
embracing all Catholics and intent upon creating a united Ireland. Mr Peter
Robinson, deputy leader of the Democratic Unionist party, is under attack
for suggesting it was 'probably logical that people in the loyalist
community have seen that terrorism has worked for the IRA and feel that they
can make it work for themselves'.
Neither have the police escaped criticism. Mr Alex Attwood, a Belfast SDLP
councillor, said he believed officers at 'lower levels' in the RUC were
'turning a blind eye' to potential attacks in Catholic areas. The RUC denies
this.
The RUC is in no doubt that, if the IRA again steps up its campaign, the
loyalist paramilitaries will do the same. The security forces believe that,
while loyalist extremists may not be so well organised, the numbers of
highly motivated, active volunteers are on a par with those of the IRA and
their weaponry has been improving.
Recent disclosures of a 'doomsday' plan by the UDA involving the creation of
an 'ethnically pure' Protestant homeland in the event of a republican
'victory' and British withdrawal from Northern Ireland, were treated with
scepticism by politicians. But they raised the spectre of loyalist
paramilitaries replacing the IRA as the prime architects of violence in the
event of a political settlement in the north.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
    P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
