<HEADLINE>
FT  17 FEB 94 / World Trade News: US poised to take lead in digital HDTV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US is set to take world leadership in digital high-definition television
(HDTV) following the announcement yesterday of a final decision on
establishing technical standards for the new generation of TV technology.
HDTV is expected to provide crisper television pictures. It will, however,
require consumers to buy new television sets.
The US 'Digital HDTV Grand Alliance' - a group of companies that have been
developing HDTV technology for the US market - said that it had made its
final major technical decision by selecting technology from Zenith for
digital transmission of HDTV signals via terrestrial broadcast or cable
systems.
The announcement marks the end of months of testing of various aspects of
HDTV technology by the Grand Alliance together with the Federal
Communications Commission.
The Digital HDTV standard represents the merging of technologies from the
three groups that had developed digital HDTV systems for consideration as
the US standard. The parties involved are: AT&amp;T and Zenith Electronics,
General Instrument and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, and a
consortium composed of Thomson Consumer Electronics, Philips Consumer
Electronics and the David Sarnoff Research Center.
The companies agreed to co-operate last May, at the urging of the FCC, which
asked the rival industry groups to combine the best features of each of
their HDTV technology to create a 'best of the best' standard. The complete
Grand Alliance HDTV system is now scheduled for final verification testing
in late 1994 and field testing in early 1995.
The US digital HDTV system, unlike Japan's analogue system, is compatible
with computers and digital telecommunications technologies as well as
television. It is therefore expected to play a central role in the
establishment of the National Information Infrastructure (NII), known as the
'information superhighway'.
</TEXT>
