<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / Government Bonds: Investors go for safety first in volatile
environment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CONNER MIDDELMANN and FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
European government bonds had another volatile day, with the higher-yielding
markets posting the largest losses and the core markets benefiting from
their perceived status as safe havens amid widespread nervousness.
'In this volatile environment, investors opt for safety-plays in the core
markets,' said Mr Andre de Silva, a market strategist at Paine Webber in
London, noting that the yield premiums on Italian, Spanish and Swedish bonds
over German bunds have widened significantly over the past two weeks.
In the UK, gilts ended a choppy session slightly lower despite encouraging
economic data. Gilt futures hit the day's high after the release of much
weaker-than-expected December manufacturing output and industrial production
figures, but drifted lower as follow-through cash buying failed to
materialise.
The announcement of the terms for next week's gilt auction had little impact
on the market, although traders were cheered by the size of the auction,
which was at the low end of market expectations.
Otherwise, the details were in line with forecasts: the Bank will auction
Pounds 2.5bn of the existing 7 per cent gilt due 2001 next Wednesday. The
issue will be partly paid, with 50 per cent payable on April 11, and is Free
of Tax to Residents Abroad (Fotra). When-issued trading began yesterday.
Gilt traders today will focus on the announcement of the January retail
prices index and retail sales data.
German bunds saw another trendless day amid thin volume as parts of Germany
were closed for a holiday. The bund future fell on comments from Mr Gunther
Rexrodt, the German economics minister, who said that he did not expect
German interest rates to decline in the near term.
Although the D-Mark firmed against the dollar and some ERM currencies, few
market participants expect the Bundesbank to lower interest rates at its
council meeting on Thursday as long as the pay dispute in the engineering
sector continues.
Italian and Spanish bonds continued to slide as investors shifted into
lower-yielding core markets. The Italian futures contract on Liffe dropped
by 0.97 point to 116.27, pressured by the 10-year bond auction, where the
yield rose to 7.59 per cent from 7.36 per cent at the previous auction in
January.
The Madrid-based Spanish bond future fell by 0/70 point to 104.98. Prices
remain pressured by recent bearish inflation indicators and selling by
overseas investors.
Supported by the weak stock market and the strong yen, Japanese government
bonds continued their recent rally but late profit-taking erased most gains,
leaving them only slightly firmer at the close.
Nevertheless, Mr Mark Hale, senior economist at Sakura Finance, expects the
yield on the JGB No. 157 to ease to 3.20 per cent to 3.25 per cent in the
near term, from 3.385 per cent currently, aided by the strong currency, more
evidence of the economy's weakness and an accommodating money-market stance
by the Bank of Japan ahead of year-end on March 31.
US Treasury bonds held steady yesterday as the dollar stabilised against the
yen and two readings on the economy produced no surprises.
Late in the day, the benchmark 30-year government bond was unchanged at 97
11/32 , with the yield at 6.448 per cent. On the short end, the two-year
note also showed no change at 99 7/32 , to yield 4.403 per cent.
Bonds across the maturity range held close to their opening levels despite
underlying concern over trade relations between the US and Japan. The long
end had slumped in the previous session after tensions between the two
triggered a downturn in the value of the dollar against the yen.
But the US currency firmed yesterday, easing fears the Japanese investors
would sell off their dollar-denominated holdings. The longer-dated
securities drifted higher, but eased later in the afternoon.
The day's economic news was largely in line with expectations. The Federal
Reserve reported January industrial production up 0.5 per cent, against a
revised 0.9 per cent in December.
Capacity utilisation, which is keenly watched as a measure of inflationary
potential, edged up to 83.1 per cent, from 82.9 per cent the previous month.
Neither set of data was conclusive enough to influence sentiment.
</TEXT>
<XX>
