<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / International Bonds: Sweden raises Pounds 200m with
five-year Eurobonds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Kingdom of Sweden took advantage of the temporary strength in the UK
government bond market yesterday afternoon to raise Pounds 200m through an
issue of Eurobonds with a five-year maturity.
The pricing of the bonds, to yield 24 basis points over the 6 per cent UK
government bond due 1999, was widely regarded as fair and reflected the
yield spread on Sweden's sterling-denominated paper in the secondary market.
Lead managers IBJ International and UBS said that most of the demand for the
issue came from Europe.
The proceeds of the deal, which remained in syndicate overnight, were
thought to have been swapped into floating-rate dollars. Some syndicate
managers noted, however, that the pricing of the bonds on its own would not
have allowed Sweden to achieve its perceived dollar funding target of around
10 to 12 basis points below Libor.
The other main deal of the day was a Dollars 300m 10-year offering of
Eurobonds from the US financial subsidiary of BMW, the German car
manufacturer, which has an implied single-A rating. The bonds, which were
priced to yield 66 basis points over 10-year US Treasuries, were deemed to
be expensive when compared with yield spreads on outstanding 10-year
dollar-denominated paper by other single-A corporates.
Lead managers Dresdner Bank and Goldman Sachs reported solid demand for the
bonds from Italy, Switzerland and France but said that German interest was
muted because of a public holiday in parts of Germany. Nevertheless, when
the bonds were freed to trade, they slipped from their fixed re-offer price
of 99.85 to 99.75 and the spread widened to 69 basis points, according to
some dealers.
Elsewhere, Region d'Ile de France, the French local authority, raised
FFr800m through an offering of eight-year Eurobonds which were priced to
yield 25 basis points over the French government bond yield curve. Lead
manager CCF said the bonds appealed to French institutions and retail
investors in Switzerland. Generale des Eaux is expected to launch a FFr2bn
offering of eight-year Eurobonds as early as today at a yield spread of
between 45 to 50 basis points over French government bonds.
The European Investment Bank was also thought to be taking bids from four
investment banks for a Dollars 500m offering of 10-year Eurobonds. The price
talk on the deal was between five and 10 basis points over the old US
treasury. Syndicate managers said the spread on the EIB's deal could
influence the pricing on the Asian Development Bank's forthcoming Dollars
750m offering of global bonds.
The market also expects the Kingdom of Belgium to raise as much as DM1bn in
the Eurobond market in the near future. The issuer is believed to favour a
10-year maturity but some syndicate managers believed that it would be able
to achieve better pricing if it opted for a maturity of between five and
seven years.
</TEXT>
