FT  16 FEB 94 / International Company News: Mexican brewer in Dollars 533m
share issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Grupo Modelo, Mexico's largest brewing group, and its owners are set to sell
12 per cent of the company's share capital today in a two-tranche initial
public offering worth 1.65bn pesos (Dollars 533m), writes Damian Fraser in
Mexico.
The primary and secondary offers, totalling 24.3m shares, at 68 pesos per
share comprise the biggest domestic share issue of a non-financial group in
recent Mexican history. They value the whole company at 13.77bn pesos, or
38.5 times earnings and 2.3 times book value.
Modelo will become one of Mexico's most valuable companies, in terms of
market capitalisation, and its shares will trade at a premium to those of
Femsa, its main competitor.
Best known for its popular Corona beer, Modelo accounts for more than half
of Mexico's domestic beer market and two-thirds of the country's exports.
The company will sell 5 per cent of its share capital in the primary
offering, and its owners another 7 per cent in the secondary offering.
Modelo said it would use part of the proceeds from the primary share
offering to build a new brewery in the state of Zacatecas.
